<div id="aueditable"><!--DO NOT MODIFY THIS LINE AND ABOVE-->

<h1>Theories of Meaning</h1><div id="pubinfo"><em>First published Tue Jan 26, 2010; substantive revision Wed Jul 31, 2024</em></div>

<div id="preamble">

<p>
The term &ldquo;theory of meaning&rdquo; has figured, in one way or
another, in a great number of philosophical disputes over the last
century. Unfortunately, this term has also been used to mean a great
number of different things. In this entry, the focus is on two sorts
of &ldquo;theory of meaning&rdquo;. The first sort of theory&mdash;a
semantic theory&mdash;is a theory which assigns semantic contents to
expressions of a language. The second sort of theory&mdash;a
metasemantic theory&mdash;is a theory which states the facts in virtue
of which expressions have the semantic contents that they have.
Following a brief introduction, these two kinds of theory are
discussed in turn.</p>
</div> 

<div id="toc"><!--Entry Contents-->
<ul>
	<li><a href="#TwoKindTheoMean">1. Two Kinds of Theory of Meaning</a></li>
	<li><a href="#SemaTheo">2. Semantic Theories</a>
